We will keep track of this as we trim observations from the set of outliers, which in some cases, will result in lost information - so there is a tradeoff when cleaning that must be negotiated.

Here we entertain two methodologies for cleaning data: 1) deletion; vs.Â 2) deletetion only when necessary. The latter method results in less lost information from trimming outlier data.

##part c)
NHIS_1<-subset(NHIS, SLEEP<=24) ##deletes observations with invalid sleep response
dim(NHIS_1)  ##dimensions of the data after 1st step
## [1] 4657    9
(dim(NHIS)[1]-dim(NHIS_1)[1])/dim(NHIS)[1]  ##computes fraction of data lost in first step of cleaning
## [1] 0.02675026

Note that we lost about 2% of the observations from removing the outliers on the SLEEP variable. Cleaning up the remainder in sequence per the instructions:

##part d)
NHIS_2<-subset(NHIS_1, height<90)
dim(NHIS_2)  ##dimensions of the data after 2nd step
## [1] 4323    9
NHIS_3<-subset(NHIS_2, weight<450)
dim(NHIS_3)  ##dimensions of the data after 3rd step
## [1] 4211    9
NHIS_4<-subset(NHIS_3, BMI<60)
dim(NHIS_4)  ##dimensions of the data after 4th step
## [1] 4211    9
NHIS_5<-subset(NHIS_4, educ<35)
dim(NHIS_5)  ##dimensions of the data after 5th step
## [1] 4189    9

Alternatively, we could have done all of the steps at once:

##part e)
NHIS_A<-subset(NHIS, SLEEP<=24 & BMI<60 & educ<35 & height<90 & weight<450)

##part f)

we have lost about 12% of the total observations from outlier removal (deletion).

R will not be able to unless we tell it to ignore cases where there is an NA and to use only the other relevant information, resulting in minimal information loss.

Problem 3

We will now use the power_plants.txt dataset to build some linear regression models.

##part a)
plot(power_plants$GrossCons, power_plants$Energy, col=factor(power_plants$PhaseI))
legend("bottomright", legend=c('Regulated Plants', 'Unregulated Plants'), pch = c(1,1), col = c(2,1))

By observing the diagram above, there seems to be a strong linear relationship between energy output and gross energy consumption. The slope of the plot looks to be close to 1/3, but we will have to verify with a linear model:

##part b)
M1<-lm(Energy ~ GrossCons, power_plants)
summary(M1)
##

## lm(formula = Energy ~ GrossCons, data = power_plants)

plot(power_plants$GrossCons, power_plants$Energy, col=factor(power_plants$PhaseI))
legend("bottomright", legend=c('Regulated Plants', 'Unregulated Plants'), pch = c(1,1), col = c(2,1))
abline(M1, lty=1, col = 4, lwd= 3)  ##adds blue regression line to diagram

The coefficient on GrossCons is approximately 1/3 (and it is statistically significant). An additional unit of energy consumed generates only 1/3 of a unit of output, implying that about 2/3 of energy consumption is wasted/ The model explains about 99% of the variation in energy output across firm-years when controlling for gross consumption of energy inputs only.

Note that when we reverse the role of the regressors and the regressand (the x and the y variables), the slope coefficient becomes exactly 1/(Slope of Original), so that the slope of the regression model with the variable roles exchanged is inverted compared to the original model. Otherwise, everything else looks about the same in terms of statistical significance, goodness of fit (R-squared), and the plot of the regression line in the same diagrammatic space.

##part g)
summary(M1$residuals)
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
## -5.82714 -0.30951  0.01323  0.00000  0.30073  4.21337
hist(M1$residuals, breaks=30, prob=TRUE)
##overlay zero mean normal distribution
curve(dnorm(x, mean = 0, sd = sd(M1$residuals)), col = "darkblue", lwd = 2, add = TRUE)

By looking at the empirical distribution of the residuals, we see that the mean is approximately zero (in fact, we cannot reject that null hypothesis). This is a characteristic of the OLS process - that the residuals will have an average value of zero - there is no BIAS in the estimates. We are, ON AVERAGE, not overshooting or undershooting with our predictive model. However, if you force the regression line through the origin, then this may not be the case - the residuals may have a nonzero mean which results in a systematic bias, but there may be reasons to tradeoff some bias say, to reduce variance in generalizing to out-of-sample predictions on datapoints the model âhasnât seen.â

In all of the other model iterations (M2-M5) where we forced the regression through the origin, the mean of the residual errors is not zero (not apparent from the histograms with normal density overlay), meaning weâve accepted some bias in the estimation in order to improve the fit of the model (in accordance with physical principles).

Problem 6

Part a) essentially asks us to compute the following probability using the cumulative distribution function (CDF) for the standard normal distribution: F(1)-F(-1)

##Part a
pnorm(1,0,1)-pnorm(-1,0,1)
## [1] 0.6826895

Similarly,

##Part b
pnorm(2,0,1)-pnorm(-2,0,1)
## [1] 0.9544997

Likewise,

##Part c
pnorm(3,0,1)-pnorm(-3,0,1)
## [1] 0.9973002

Part d): Observing the probabilities above should be consistent with Chebychevâs rule - that 68% of the data lie within one standard deviation of the mean, 95% within two, and 99.7% within threeâ¦ Part e) essentially asks us to compute 1-F(2.5) for the standard normal distribution for only a single (right side) tail:

##Part e
1-pnorm(2.5,0,1)
## [1] 0.006209665

Similarly, part f) asks for the right tail probability, but also adds the left tail probability (since it asks about values more extreme in absolute value implying that they could be positive or negative):

##Part f
1-pnorm(1.5,0,1)+pnorm(-1.5,0,1)
## [1] 0.1336144
##OR, by symmetry of the distriubtion, we could have computed the size of one tail and doubled it

The final part of problem 2 (part g) essentially asks us to consider the conditional probability: P(X between 2 and 3| X bigger than 1)=P(X between 2 and 3 intersect X bigger than 1)/P(X bigger than 1) by Bayeâs. Note that if x is between two it must also be bigger than one so that the numerator is the same as P(X between 2 and 3), which is F(3)-F(2) using the standard normalâs CDF. The denominator of the expression, P(X bigger than 1)is just the compliment of F(1). Thus, the probability that we need to compute is (F(3)-F(2))/(1-F(1)):

##Part g
(pnorm(3,0,1)-pnorm(2,0,1))/(1-pnorm(1,0,1))
## [1] 0.1348851

Problem 7

This problem is essentially an empirical verification of the CLT. Below, we sample 10000 draws from the uniform distribution (on the interval [0,1]) and plot the empirical distribution:

##Part a
x<-runif(10000,0,1)
hist(x, breaks = 30, prob = TRUE, xlim=c(--.1,1.1), ylim=c(0,1.1))

Note that it is approximately flat (as we expect for the uniform distribution). To empirically âverifyâ the CLT, we will sample 30 observations, compute the sample mean, and repeat this process 1000 times so that we have 1000 sample means estimated (each slightly different since the data being drawn each time isnât the same at each repitition of the 30 draws of data). We use a for loop to run the âexperimentâ over 1000 repetitions without having to do so manually:

reps<-1000
draws<- 30
rv <- NULL  ##place holder for the variable
normed <- NULL  ##place holder for the variable
b<-1  ##assigns endpoint to the uniform distribution
a<-0  ##assigns endpoint to the uniform distribution
mu<-1/2*(b+a) ##this is the actual population mean for the uniform distriubtion (the center of the rectangle)

for (i in 1:reps){  ##this for loop does the same thing indexing over the values of the repetitions
  rv<-runif(draws, 0, 1)  ##draw a sample for this repetition
  xbar<-mean(rv)  ##computes the sample mean for this particular set of draws
  se<-((1/12)*(b-a)^2)^.5/sqrt(draws)  ##computes the small sample standard error
  normed[i]<-(xbar-mu)/se  ##normalizes the sample data and stores the average for this repetition of draws in a vector that will be added to at each repetition with the new sample mean
}

Now we will plot the 1000 sample means that were generated by sampling from a uniform flat) distribution:

hist(normed, density = 10, breaks = 30, prob = TRUE, ylim = c(0,.5), xlim = c(-4,4))
curve(dnorm(x, mean = 0, sd = 1), col = "darkblue", lwd = 2, add = TRUE)

Note that the sample means, which were calculated as averages of draws from a flat distribution, are approximately normally distributed despite the underlying distribution the data was being sampled from was uniformly generated. This tells us that the normal distribution is widely applicable to a variety of problems in statistics - the CLT essentially implies that the assumption of normality may be reasonable in many cases.

E_IN
## [1] 0

To compute the out-of-sample error, we must measure the squared deviation of the hypothesis from the DGP (distance from the blue line and the red line at each value of the x-variable sampled):

#part g-h
y_DGP=B_0+B_1*x_synth
E_OUT<-sqrt(sum((hyp$fitted.values-y_DGP)^2/n))
E_OUT
## [1] 0.5067299

If we repeat the same experiment but increase the sample size, we should see two things: first, the linear hypothesis will not be able to perfectly fit more than two points (unless the points sampled all randomly happen to fall in line, and this happens with zero probability). As a consequence, the in-sample error (E_IN) will increase as we sample more points for the same complexity of hypothesis (linear with a single feature). The second thing we should see happen is an improvement with out out-of-sample error from an increased sample size since our estimates of the population parameters will have smaller standard errors:
